# ------------------------ START COMMIT MESSAGE ------------------------
# <type>(<scope>)!: <description>
# |<------ preferably using 50 characters ------->|<-----(72 max)----->|

# Optional <body>
# |<------------------ 72 characters maximum per line ---------------->|

# Optional <footer>
# |<------------------ 72 characters maximum per line ---------------->|

# ------------------------- END COMMIT MESSAGE -------------------------
#
# <type>: What type of commit this is
#   - feat:     New features
#   - fix:	Bug fixes
#   - build:	Changes in build system or environment
#   - test:	Adding new tests or correcting defective tests
#   - docs:	Changes in documentation only
#   - refactor:	For rewriting or restructuring code that does not affect behavior
#   - style:	Changes made in code styles and no changes in logic
#   - chore:	Miscellaneous tasks
#
# <scope> (Optional): What section of the code base does this apply to
#   - Allowed content changes from project to project
#   - Issue identifies are not valid scopes
#
# !: Indicates a breaking change
#
# <descripotion>: A concise description of the change
#   - Imperative (as if "This commit will..." was prepended)
#   - No capitalization at beginning or punctuation at end
#
# <body> (Optional): Additional information about code changes
#   - Multiple paragraphs can be included
#   - Imperative with proper capitalization and punctuation.
#
# <footer> (Optional): List of key-value pairs that store metadata
#  - BREAKING CHANGE: <description>	For breaking changes, can be ommited if "!" is included in subject line
#  - Automatic issue management		Reference issues (example: "Close #123", "Reference #123", "See #123", etc)
#  - Email-like metadata		Personal identifiers such as "Signed-off-by:", "Co-authored-by:", etc
#
# Special Cases:
#   - "Initial commit" 		For the first commit in a git repository
#   - "Merge branch...":	Default commit message for automatic merges
#   - "Revert...":		Default commit message for reverting commits
